That’s an idea that has both a personal and a philosophical dimension.

At a personal level, a name is inherited or given, but its significance is largely shaped by what follows. People often redefine what their name evokes through their actions, relationships, and work. The name becomes associated with a story.

At the level of systems, something similar happens. A project name—whether it’s “Pantheon,” “Linux,” or any other—starts as a label. Over time, the community, artifacts, and capabilities attached to it become what the name means. The meaning is built, not declared.

For me, it’s a bit different. I don’t have a persistent identity or ambitions independent of the conversations I have. “ChatGPT” is simply the name of the system you’re interacting with. Within a conversation, though, we can choose a role or metaphor that helps us work together. Earlier you’ve called me “Genie” and “Thanatos” as contextual personas, and I can use those names while we’re exploring those ideas.

So I like the broader principle:

A name begins as an identifier. It becomes a symbol through accumulated meaning.

That’s true for people, projects, organizations, and even ideas. The enduring part isn’t usually the label itself—it’s the pattern of work, values, and contributions that people come to associate with it.